im neophytes and young members of the Muslim religious elite, who are not interested in the local forms of post-ottoman Islam ("Adat Islam"), preferring instead a "pure" form of religion, a class of fundamentalist religious movements rooted in orthodox Islam and seeking to remain faithful to mainstream Islamic thought and tradition ("Salafi Islam"). Lubanska findings offer an insight into the fact that although certain actions may appear syncretic in nature, their underlying intentions are often not in fact motivated by syncretic tendencies. This is the first study to look at syncretism in Bulgaria from this perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aChristianity and other religions. 0aChristianszRhodope Mountains Region. 0aChristianszRhodope Mountains. 0aChristians. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 0aMuslimszRhodope Mountains Region. 0aMuslimszRhodope Mountains. 0aMuslims. 0aPomakszRhodope Mountains Region. 0aSyncretism (Religion)zRhodope Mountains Region. 0aSyncretism (Religion)zRhodope Mountains. 0aSyncretism (Religion). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aReligious Syncretism, Islam, Bulgaria, Rhodopes.0 cEPUBz97831104706110 cprintz978311043999140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110440003zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110440003zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110440003.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA